The center is the only square that participates in the greatest number of potential winning lines (four: two diagonals, one row, one column). By occupying it, X maximizes its influence over the board and forces O to respond in a way that cannot immediately create a fork or win.  

If X starts elsewhere (corner or edge), O can always play the center and gain a positional advantage, potentially forcing a draw or even a win if X blunders. The center also blocks O’s ability to create a fork on the next move because every line that could be completed by O must pass through the center.  

Thus, placing **X** in the center (row 1, column 1) is the universally accepted optimal first move, guaranteeing at least a draw and giving X the best chance to win if O errs.

