X has only one mark in the top‑left corner, so there is no immediate threat to block.  
The goal for O is to create the most forcing positions while keeping all of X’s potential lines open. In Tic‑Tac‑Toe the center square is the most powerful spot because it belongs to four different winning lines (row 1, column 1, and both diagonals). By occupying the center, O simultaneously:

1. **Builds two immediate threats** – if O later places another mark on either the middle row or middle column, X will have to respond to a potential win on that line.
